# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-c-black] The firm was founded in 1807 by Charles and Adam Black in Edinburgh.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-c-black] In 1851, the company purchased the copyrights to Sir Walter Scott's *Waverly* novels for £27,000.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-c-black] The company moved to the Soho district of London in 1889.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-c-black] During the years 1827–1903 the firm published the seventh, eighth and ninth editions of the *Encyclopædia Britannica*.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-c-black] This was purchased from Archibald Constable after his company's failure to publish the seventh edition of the encyclopedia.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-c-black] Adam Black retired in 1870 due to his disapproval of his sons' extravagant plans for its ninth edition.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-c-black] This edition, however, would sell half a million sets and was released in 24 volumes from 1875 to 1889.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-c-black] Beginning in 1839, the firm published a series of travel guides known as *Black's Guides*.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-c-black] The company was the publisher of the annual *Who's Who* (since 1849) and also, since 2002, the *Whitaker's Almanack*.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-c-black] Other notable works include *Black's Medical Dictionary* and the *Know The Game* series of sports rules and laws reference books.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-c-black] Black Colour Books: Twenty Shilling Series* (1901–21), a "range of high-quality colour collectable picture books" which are still collected by bibliophiles.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-c-black] Wodehouse's first book, *The Pothunters*, and went on to produce many of his early works.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-c-black] In 1989 A & C Black purchased both Christopher Helm Publishers and later the Pica Press, publishers of the Helm Identification Guides, from Christopher Helm.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-c-black] In 2000 A & C Black was purchased by Bloomsbury Publishing Plc, which continued producing the former's range of reference works.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-c-black] Poyser and their back-list of around 70 ornithology titles were acquired from Elsevier Science.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-c-black] A & C Black purchased Methuen Drama from Methuen Publishing in 2006, and acquired Arden Shakespeare from Cengage Learning in 2008.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-c-black] In 2016, A & C Black Music list moved to Collins Learning, a division of HarperCollins Publishers Ltd.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abandoned-pets] Animal welfare laws in many states of the United States make it a crime to abandon a pet.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abandoned-pets] Often, when abandoned, pets are forced to fend for themselves and become stray or feral.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abandoned-pets] Feral cats are said to outnumber feral dogs and can become challenging to handle and socialize enough to be re-introduced to a new human owner.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abandoned-pets] In general, only some newly abandoned cats and very young feral kittens can be tamed.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abandoned-pets] There is a necessity to investigate interventions to prevent companion-animal relinquishment.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abandoned-pets] Stray animals increase potential exposure to zoonotic diseases like rabies.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abandoned-pets] Cat bites or scratches involving stray or feral animals are eight times more common than dog bites.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abandoned-pets] The impacts of dog and cat predation on wildlife can also be significant.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abandoned-pets] Some pets relinquished to an animal shelter will be euthanized due to a lack of space or financial resources.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abandoned-pets] Millions of companion animals enter animal shelters every year in the United States.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abandoned-pets] However, the number of dogs and cats euthanized in US shelters declined from approximately 2.6 million in 2011 to 1.5 million in 2018.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abandoned-pets] This decline can be partially explained by an increase in the percentage of animals adopted, and an increase in the number of stray animals successfully returned to their owners.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abandoned-pets] Studies show that the majority of people who relinquish an animal also report being emotionally attached to the animal.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abandoned-pets] It has been reported that when forced to abandon their animals in an evacuation, people suffer mental issues such as grief, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abandoned-pets] Recognizing the importance of pets to their owners and their role in public health is an essential first step in improving a public health problem that has been seen repeatedly in the past and is unlikely to change in the future.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abandoned-pets] Pet abandonment increased during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abandoned-pets] In early 2009, the ASPCA published advice for people facing foreclosure and the loss of their pets, recommending finding a foster or adoption situation for your pet, being aware of rental property rules for pets, and checking with animal shelters and animal rescue groups.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] In 1995, AbeBooks was founded by Rick and Vivian Pura, and Keith and Cathy Waters.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] It was incorporated in 1995 and launched its websites in 1996, initially including listings for only four bookstores.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] The company name "Abebooks" is derived from their original name, "Advanced Book Exchange".
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] From the late 1990s to 2005, AbeBooks had reseller agreements with eBay, Half.com, Barnes & Noble.com, BibliOZ.com and Amazon.com, allowing AbeBooks to market and sell booksellers' books through those channels; these agreements were dissolved in 2005.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] AbeBooks currently has a reseller agreement only with Amazon.com.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] In 2001, AbeBooks acquired Germany's JustBooks GmbH online book marketplace, which helped the company expand into the German, French and British online bookselling markets.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] In 2002, the founding partners were bought out by German media company Hubert Burda Media.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] In 2004, the company expanded its model to include new books, and acquired the Spanish company IberLibro, to better serve Spanish language markets.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] In 2005, it acquired BookFinder.com, an American book price comparison service.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] In 2006, the company acquired Fillz, a book-inventory and order-management company, and purchased a 40% stake in LibraryThing in May, a social networking and book cataloging website for bibliophiles.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] In June 2008 AbeBooks was awarded the British Columbia Technology Industry Association Impact Award for Leadership in Social Responsibility for its charitable activities, literacy initiatives, and commitment to environmental friendliness in its business practices.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] In December 2008, the company was sold to Amazon.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] In 2018, the company announced it would no longer fully support sellers from a number of countries, including South Korea, Hungary, and the Czech Republic.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] Several hundred other sellers pulled their inventories from the AbeBooks site in protest.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] AbeBooks is headquartered in Victoria, British Columbia, Canada, with its European office in Düsseldorf, Germany.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] The company manages regional websites for North America, France, Germany, Italy, the UK and Spain.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] Most of its inventory consists of used books, including rare, signed, first editions or out of print books.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] It has been named one of British Columbia's Top Employers every year since 2008.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] In February 2015, ABE recorded its most expensive sales up to that time: a rare illustrated ornithology book was sold on behalf of one of its dealers for $191,000.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] Other high-end sales included *Areopagitica: A Speech for the Liberty of Unlicenc'd Printing To the Parliament of England* by John Milton and a first edition of *The Hobbit* by J.R.R.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] The website periodically reports their recent high value sales.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] AbeBooks' users can search across the listings of many independent bookstores.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] Some of the member bookstores offer their books online only, while others also maintain a regular storefront.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] Booksellers upload their inventory data to the AbeBooks database, specifying information about each book including condition and price.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] Prices are fixed (with US$1 being the minimum) and there are no auctions.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] Items available range from the extremely common, where there might be hundreds of copies listed, to first editions and signed books worth thousands of dollars.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] In addition to books, the marketplace also offers periodicals and journals, fine art such as prints and posters, vintage photographs, maps, sheet music and paper ephemera such as postcards, letters and other documents.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] Sellers pay a monthly subscription to list their books on the site, ranging from $25 to $500, depending on how many books they list.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] This subscription fee has been in place since at least April 2008.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] In addition, sellers pay a percentage fee for each book sold via the websites.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] AbeBooks initially offered its services for a flat listings fee, based on the number of titles listed for sale.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] The model was changed in the early 2000s to include a commission on sales.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] In April 2006 AbeBooks started mandatory processing of MasterCard and Visa credit card transactions on behalf of its sellers and added a 5.5% charge for the provision of this service: previously this service had been optional.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] In 2008, AbeBooks started charging a commission of 13.5% on the cost of postage as well as the book price.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] Currently (2013) the commission charge is set at 8% of postage and book price.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] Sellers can, within limits, set their own standard postage rates to various countries or by different carriers.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] Booksellers can upload their inventory using their own spreadsheet software or via the site's interface.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] Items that sell are mailed directly from the individual bookseller's location.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] Some booksellers have new books directly mailed from wholesalers or publishers.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] Most booksellers who list on AbeBooks also list their books on similar marketplaces such as Amazon.com.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abebooks] Similar websites include BookFinder.com and LibraryThing.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists disagree on the strategy that must be used to achieve their goal.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists such as Steven Best and David Nibert argue, respectively, that embracing alliance politics and militant direct action for change (including civil disobedience, mass confrontation, etc), and transcending capitalism are integral to ending animal exploitation.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists generally oppose movements that seek to make animal use more humane or to abolish specific forms of animal use, since they believe this undermines the movement to abolish all forms of animal use.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] The objective is to secure a moral and legal paradigm shift, whereby animals are no longer regarded as things to be owned and used.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] The American philosopher Tom Regan writes that abolitionists want empty cages, not bigger ones.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] This is contrasted with animal welfare, which seeks incremental reform, and animal protectionism, which seeks to combine the first principles of abolitionism with an incremental approach, but which is regarded by some abolitionists as another form of welfarism or "New Welfarism".
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] The word relates to the historical term abolitionism—a social movement to end slavery or human ownership of other humans.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] Based on the way of evaluating welfare reforms, abolitionists can be either radical or pragmatic.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] While the former maintain that welfare reforms can only be dubiously described as moral improvements, the latter consider welfare reforms as moral improvements even when the conditions they permit are unjust.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] He calls such groups the "new welfarists", arguing that, though their aim is an end to animal use, the reforms they pursue are indistinguishable from reforms agreeable to traditional welfarists, who he says have no interest in abolishing animal use.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] He argues that reform campaigns entrench the property status of animals, and validate the view that animals simply need to be treated better.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] Instead, he writes, the public's view that animals can be used and consumed ought to be challenged.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] His position is that this should be done by promoting ethical veganism.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] Others think that this should be done by creating a public debate in society.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] He rhetorically asks, how can one hope to create some consumer base for this new vegan world when over a billion people live on less than a dollar a day?
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] Nibert acknowledges that post-capitalism on its own will not automatically end animal exploitation or bring about a more just world, but that it is a "necessary precondition" for such changes.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] New welfarists argue that there is no logical or practical contradiction between abolitionism and "welfarism".
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] Welfarists think that they can be working toward abolition, but by gradual steps, pragmatically taking into account what most people can be realistically persuaded to do in the short as well as the long term, and reduce animal suffering as it is most urgent to relieve.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, for example, in addition to promoting local improvements in the treatment of animals, promote vegetarianism.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] Although some people believe that changing the legal status of nonhuman sentient beings is a first step in abolishing ownership or mistreatment, others argue that this will not succeed if the consuming public has not already begun to reduce or eliminate its exploitation of animals for food.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 1992, Switzerland amended its constitution to recognize animals as *beings* and not *things*.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] The dignity of animals is also protected in Switzerland.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] New Zealand granted basic rights to five great ape species in 1999.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] Their use is now forbidden in research, testing or teaching.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] Germany added animal welfare in a 2002 amendment to its constitution, becoming the first European Union member to do so.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2007, the parliament of the Balearic Islands, an autonomous province of Spain, passed the world's first legislation granting legal rights to all great apes.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2013, India officially recognized dolphins as non-human persons.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2014, France revised the legal status of animals from movable property to sentient beings.
[src:a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2015, the province of Quebec in Canada adopted the Animal Welfare and Safety Act, which gave animals the legal status of "sentient beings with biological needs".
